An offshore coral reef also seems to have prevented much more widespreaddestruction on the low-lying Maldives islands, Cripps noted.
"There is a huge natural cost, but what it is is still to bedetermined," said Lynne Hale, director of the global marineinitiative for the Nature Conservancy, who worked in Thailand'sPhuket Island and Sri Lanka for many years.
On Phuket Island, one popular beach was piled withdead staghorn coral, starfish, gulper eels, sea cucumbers, and seagrasses.
The death toll in the catastrophe in Indonesia's Aceh and NorthSumatra provinces alone reached more than 80,000 on Thursday.
